In this exam, we investigate the ChickWeight dataset in R. You can load the data using the following commands. Carefully read the help file of ChickWeight before working on the following questions.

data(ChickWeight)

(a) Briefly summarize all variables in the data set. You need to provide the definition of the variable and quantitative summary.

Solution: (Type your answer here)

Weight represents the body weight of chicken, and is a numeric vector.

Time represents the number of days from birth as the measurement was made.

Chick is an ordered factor with 50 levels, and is a unique identifier for the chick. The levels ordering puts together chicks on the same diet and arranges them from lightest to heaviest in terms of final weight.

Diet is an factor with 4 levels, which represent the diet type the chick recieved

(c) Write down an appropriate one-way ANOVA model to answer the question whether there is any changes in mean weights at Day 20 across the four diet group. To receive full credits, you need to (i) write down the model, explain your notation, constraint(s) and/or assumptions; (ii) state the null and alternative hypotheses; (iii) state the test result. You can find basic LaTeX commands at the end of this file.

Solution: (Type your answer here)

\(Y_{ij}=\mu_{..}+\alpha_i+\epsilon_{ij}\) i=1,2,3,4, j=1,2..\(n_{i}\)

\(\mu_{..} :\) represents the overall mean weight of chick at day 20.

\(\alpha_i :\) represents the fixed effect of \(i^{th}\) diet type, \(\sum_{i=1}^{4} \alpha_i=0\).

  • i=1: diet type=1

  • i=2: diet type=2

  • i=3: diet type=3

  • i=4: diet type=4

\(\epsilon_{ij} :\) represents the residual of \(j^{th}\) chicks weight at \(i^{th}\) diet type. \(\epsilon_{ij} \sim N(0,\sigma^2)\)

Due to the unbalanced data, the first diet type has 17 data points, the fourth diet type has 9 data points, and the third and second diet types have 10 data points each. Therefore, we will use a Type II ANOVA to answer this question.

# (c). (Type your code in the space below, if any)
library(pander)
data_c<-ChickWeight[ChickWeight$Time==20,]
data_c%>%group_by(Diet)%>%summarise(count=n())->one_way_count
pander(one_way_count)
Diet count
1 17
2 10
3 10
4 9

hypothesis:

\(H_0 :\space \alpha_i=0\) for i in 1,2,3,4

\(H_1: \space \alpha_i \neq0\) for i in 1,2,3,4

Based on the F test, we learn that the p-value (2.909 x \(10^{-3}\)) is small enough, p-value is smaller than 0.01, to reject the null hypothesis. Hence, we will keep \(\alpha_i\) in this model.

fit.1=lm(weight ~Diet,data=data_c)
fit.1=car::Anova(fit.1, type = 2)
fit.1

(d) For the model fitted in (c), carry out necessary diagnostics to check if the model assumptions are valid. What are your findings?

Solution: (Type your answer here)

homogeneity of variance assumption

\(H_0:\space \sigma^2_1=\sigma^2_2=\sigma^2_3=\sigma^2_4\)

\(H_0 :\space\sigma^2_i\neq\sigma^2_j\) i=1,2,3,4, j=1,2,3,4, \(i \neq j\)

p-value bigger than 0.05, so we do not reject null hypothesis, the model follow variance of homogeneity, known as homoscedasticity.

(f) We want to take the chick-specific effect into account. The new mixed effect model is based on the model in (e), where Time is treated as a continuous covariate instead of a categorical factor, and a random intercept and a random slope (of Time) are added into the model. Report the fitted coefficients of the fixed effects, and summarize your findings from this model. Hint: You do not need to write down the new model, but you may find it helpful.

Solution: (Type your answer here)

\(Y_{ijk}=\mu_{}+\alpha_i+\beta_j+\epsilon_{ijk}\)

\(Y_{ijk} :\) represents the weight of \(k^{th}\) chick under \(i^{th}\) diet type and \(j^{th}\) time.

\(\mu_{} :\) represents the overall mean weight of \(k^{th}\) chick under \(i^{th}\) diet type at \(j^{th}\) time.

\(\alpha_i :\) represents the fixed effect of \(i^{th}\) diet type. \(\sum_{i=1}^{4}\alpha_i=0\)

\(\beta_j :\) represents the random effect of \(j^{th}\) time. \(\beta_j\sim N(0,\sigma_{\beta}^2)\)

\(\epsilon_{ijk}:\) represents the residual of weights of \(k^{th}\) chick across \(i^{th}\) diet type and \(j^{th}\) time.\(\epsilon_{ij} \sim N(0,\sigma^2)\)

Besides, proportion of variability that is due to variability in time is 63.5%, which is calculated from \(\sigma_{\beta}/(\sigma_{\beta}+\sigma)\).

The fitted coefficients of the fixed effects:

  • i=1: diet type=1, fitted coefficient=0, because we take type 1 diet as baseline.

  • i=2: diet type=2, fitted coefficient=16.13

  • i=3: diet type=3, fitted coefficient=36.46

  • i=4: diet type=4, fitted coefficient=30.29

Based on the coefficients that have been fitted above, it is clear that diet 3 will be the most effective in promoting weight gain in chicks.
